ne and the Oresteia by considering the meanings of tragedy for ancient Athenian audiences while also unveiling the reverberations of Greek tragedy's formulations and dilemmas in modern political life and for contemporary political philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCity-stateszGreece. 0aGender identity in literature. 0aGender identityzGreece. 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzGreece. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aLiterature : Drama. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 7aDRAMA / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBrault, Pascale-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchan, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurian, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCoskey, Denise Eileen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMccoskey, Denise Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Elaine P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrmand, Kirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchur, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShepherdson, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWohl, Wohl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZakin, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZakin, Emily, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backli